{Morphy on the Attack --- Here we have a typical King's Gambit scenario; White
has sacrificed a piece to expose the enemy king.} 10. e5 $2 {With this
surprising method of opening the e-file Morphy wants to win by direct attack.
There will be no material compensation. This move is reminiscent of a boxer,
staking everything in search of a knockout in the final round.} ({It is not
possible to regain the piece yet with} 10. Bxg8 $2 {in view of} h5 $1 {.
Nevertheless, White has very reasonable compensation. So far he has only one
pawn for the piece, but the f4-pawn looks as if it will fall soon. However,
the most important factor is that it will take the black king some time to
reach a safe haven.}) ({Morphy was only twelve years old when he played this
game. With greater maturity he would surely have gone for} 10. d4 $1 {, a
developing move which also builds a strong centre. Then after} Kd8 (10... Qxd4
$2 {would allow} 11. Bxg8 {, since the g6-square is now accessible to the
white queen}) {, White could play} 11. Bxf4 {, not fearing} d5 {on account of}
12. Qg3 dxc4 $2 13. Be5 {. --- The move chosen by the young Morphy, in his
first meeting with a well-known master, is inferior, but is testament to his
tremendous imagination and his quest for the initiative at all costs.}) 10...
Qxe5+ 11. Kd1 Kd8 {This move is fine;} ({although} 11... Nf6 {was also
adequate, enabling the black queen to retreat to h5.}) 12. Re1 ({With the
c8-bishop defended,} 12. Bxg8 $2 {would fail to} d6 ({or} 12... d5) 13. Qg6 Bf5
14. Qf7 Bg4+ {and wins; of course Morphy's idea was not to take on g8 but to
attack.}) 12... Qc5 $2 {So Morphy emerges the winner from this game of
"chicken".} ({After} 12... Qg7 $1) ({or} 12... Nf6 $1 {, he would have met
insoluble difficulties in justifying his daring 10th move.}) 13. Bxg8 d5 $4 {
This natural move is actually a fatal mistake;} (13... d6 {was better, and then
} 14. Qg6 ({or} 14. Be6 {with some advantage.})) {Not even the mature Morphy
could have handled this phase of the game with greater skill.} 14. Re8+ $1 {
An attractive way to draw out the enemy king, based on the key follow-up on
move 16.} Kxe8 15. Qxc8+ Ke7 16. Nxd5+ $1 {This is the essential follow-up to
14 Re8+!;} ({rather than} 16. Qxb7+ $2 Nd7 17. Qxa8 {, which surrenders the
initiative and hands Black a mating attack after} Qg1+ 18. Ke2 Qxg2+ 19. Ke1
Qg1+ 20. Ke2 f3+ $1 21. Kxf3 Ne5+ 22. Ke2 ({or} 22. Kf4 Qf2+ 23. Kxe5 Bg7#)
22... Qg2+ 23. Ke3 Qf3+ 24. Kd4 Qf2+ 25. Kxe5 Bg7# {.}) 16... Kd6 17. Qc7# 1-0

