22. Rb1 $1 {In a few moves all the white pieces will be attacking the black
king.} ({White is a pawn up and with the simple} 22. Rfe1 {his advantage would
be beyond doubt.}) ({Another idea is to return the pawn to open lines with} 22.
e5 $1 dxe5 23. Qe3 {. Morphy chooses something even more forceful.}) 22... b6
23. Rfc1 $1 ({With} 23. Rfc1 {another attacking piece comes into play,
threatening} -- 24. Rxb6 axb6 25. Nxb6+ {mating.}) 23... Qf6 24. Qe3 Ng4 25.
Nxb6+ $1 {Destruction of the defence, opening lines in decisive fashion.} axb6
({Or} 25... Ke7 26. Rc7+ $1 Kf8 27. Nd7+ {.}) 26. Rc7+ $1 Kd8 ({If} 26... Kxc7
{then} 27. Qxb6+ Kc8 ({or} 27... Kd7 28. Qa7+) 28. Qb8+ {and mates.}) 27. Qxb6
Qxf2+ 28. Qxf2 Nxf2 29. Ra7 Nh3+ ({Something similar to the game happens after
} 29... Kc8 30. Kxf2 {. Note that} Rxe4 {loses simply to} 31. Ra8+ {.}) 30.
gxh3 Kc8 31. Kf2 {. Black is defenceless against the plan of Ke3 and Rbb7,
followed by the advance of the a-pawn to a6, and Ra8 mate.} 1-0

