{Morphy and the Initiative --- White has the advantage - his pawn structure is
not favourable for an endgame, but "before the ending the gods have placed the
middlegame" (Tarrasch) and White has all his pieces in play, whereas Black's
queenside remains dormant. ---} 12. e5 $1 {With such a big dynamic advantage,
opening lines should be the priority.} ({Based on what we've seen so far, we
can assume that the thirteen-year-old Morphy would have been reluctant to
settle for the quiet move} 12. Bd2 {, even though this guarantees a clear
advantage, and would look for something better.}) 12... f5 ({Calculation
confirms that opening the position with} 12... fxg5 {helps White: he can
respond with} 13. Nxg5 Na6 {, developing a piece, is no better in view of} ({
when} 13... h6 {is refuted by the nice shot} 14. Qxg6 $1 {, exploiting the
weakness of Black's back rank.} (14. --)) 14. Rxf8+ Nxf8 ({in this line} 14...
Qxf8 {runs into} 15. Re4 {, with similar ideas}) 15. Rf1 Ng6 16. Rf3 {,
threatening} -- 17. Qxg6 hxg6 18. Rh3# {, among other things.}) 13. Nd4 $1 {
White's g5-bishop is now safe and Black cannot prevent further lines being
opened with gain of time; the safety of the black king is becoming an ever
greater problem.} f4 14. e6 $1 dxe6 15. Nxe6 Bxe6 16. Rxe6 Qc8 {The relief
that Black gains from the piece exchange does not compensate for the opening
of the e-file, as Morphy highlights with his next move.} 17. Rxg6 $1 hxg6 18.
Qxg6 Qf5 ({If} 18... Qe8 {, the confinement of the black king means that White
can play} 19. Qxe8 Rxe8 20. Rxf4 g6 ({or} 20... Kh7 21. Bf7) 21. Bf6+ {and
mates.}) 19. Rxf4 $1 {The prettiest and, at the same time, the quickest finish.
} Qxg6 ({There is no salvation in} 19... Qc5+ 20. Kh1 {, threatening 21 Qh5
mate and 21 Rh4 mate.}) 20. Rxf8+ Kh7 21. Bg8+ Kh8 22. Bf7+ Kh7 23. Bxg6+ Kxg6
24. Bf4 1-0

