{White is currently a pawn down, but the black pawn on h2 appears doomed and
then the strong white centre would start to be important. Morphy opts for
another solution. ---} 12. Qh5+ ({Capturing the intruder on h2 is not so
simple:} 12. Rf2 Kg8 13. Qf3 ({the immediate} 13. Rxh2 $2 {loses to} Ng4) 13...
Qd7 14. Rxh2 ({further preparatory moves such as} 14. Nc3 {are possible, but
after} Nc6 15. Rxh2 Be6 16. Rg2 Ng4 {, followed by ...Rf8, it is Black who has
the initiative}) 14... Bg4 15. Qg2 {can be met by} Be6 $1 {(threatening to win
material with 16...Ng4)} 16. Qg3 Nc6 {, when Black is ahead on development and
the white king has no pawn protection.}) 12... Kg8 13. Rxf6 $1 {This is the
idea, completely transforming the situation. In return for the exchange White
is able to weaken the black kingside, open the g-file, create a weakness on f6,
etc. It is not clear whether White will be objectively better, but his game is
easier, more pleasant.} gxf6 14. Nc3 Re5 $6 {Black benefits little from
driving the white queen back because, as we shall see, the rook is badly
placed here and the back rank is left weak.} ({It was better to redeploy his
precariously placed piece with} 14... Be6 $1 {, and at the same time control
the square d5. After, for instance,} 15. Bf4 Nc6 16. Kxh2 Re7 $1 {,
anticipating Rg1+, the position would offer chances to both sides.}) 15. Qf3
Qd7 ({The clumsy position of the rook on e5 means that} 15... Be6 {is not so
good now. White can play} 16. d4 $1 {, since} Qxd4 17. Qg3+ Kh8 18. Bh6 {
forces Black to return the exchange:} Rg5 19. Bxg5 fxg5 20. Qxg5 {, when White
would have the initiative; then if} Nc6 {, White could play} 21. Ng6+ $1 hxg6
22. Qh6+ Kg8 23. Qxg6+ {and the e6-bishop is lost.}) 16. Bf4 Nc6 {Returning
the exchange is again almost forced now.} ({If} 16... Re8 17. Bxh2 {, the pawn
on f6 is threatened and the g-file available for White's remaining rook with a
raging attack; for example,} Rf8 18. Rg1+ Kh8 19. Qh5 Rg8 20. Rxg8+ Kxg8 21.
Nd5 {and there is no defence.}) ({It is no better to play} 16... Bg4 17. Qg2
Rh5 {(controlling d5 and f5)} ({if} 17... Re8 {instead, then} 18. Nd5) {
, since after} 18. Nf5 Rxf5 19. exf5 Qxf5 20. Rf1 Nd7 21. Nd5 {(threatening
forks on e7 and e3)} Qh5 22. Ne3 f5 23. Bxc7 {(threatening to take on f5)} Rf8
24. Qxb7 {, material is now equal, while the black position is very weak.}) 17.
Kxh2 {This keeps all options open and enables the rook to use the g1-square;} (
{but in this case it appears that it was better for White to "content himself"
with} 17. Bxe5 Nxe5 ({it is worse to play} 17... fxe5 {, as after} 18. Kxh2 Bg4
19. Rg1 h5 20. Nd5 {, all the white pieces are in the game}) 18. Qxf6 Ng4 19.
Qf3 Qd4 {and now} 20. Nf5 {, when material is once again equal and White's
advantage is clear.}) 17... Bg4 18. Rg1 h5 $2 {As often happened with Morphy's
opponents, Bird fails to withstand the tension of the struggle.} (18... Rg5 $1
{was much more tenacious: after} 19. Qg3 h5 20. Bxg5 fxg5 21. Nf5 {, White is
slightly better, but the struggle can continue with} Rf8 ({or} 21... Nd4 {
. In contrast, Black's position now goes rapidly downhill.})) 19. Bxe5 fxe5 20.
Nd5 Nd4 $2 21. Nf6+ Kh8 ({Or} 21... Kf7 22. Qf2 {.}) 22. Qe3 ({Another way was
to launch an immediate assault with} 22. Ng6+ $1 Kg7 23. Nxh5+ {, when} Kxg6 ({
and} 23... Kh6 24. Qf6 Qe6 25. Rxg4 {is no better}) 24. Rxg4+ {just wins.})
22... Qg7 23. Nxh5 {The last shred of protection is stripped away from the
black king. White now has the attack and a material advantage as well, so the
rest is very simple for Morphy.} Qh7 24. Rxg4 Qxh5 25. Qh3 Kh7 26. c3 Ne6 27.
Rg6 ({Also good was} 27. Ng6 Qxh3+ 28. Kxh3 {and the e5-pawn falls.}) 27... Re8
({Here} 27... Qe2+ {would change nothing: after} 28. Rg2 Qh5 {, White can play}
29. Rg3 {.}) 28. Rxe6 Rxe6 29. Qxe6 Qxh4+ 30. Qh3 Qxh3+ 31. Kxh3 {The pawn
endgame with an extra pawn is easily won.} c5 32. Kg4 Kg6 33. Kf3 Kf6 34. Ke3
Ke6 35. d4 exd4+ 36. cxd4 cxd4+ 37. Kxd4 Kd6 38. e5+ Ke6 39. Ke4 Ke7 40. Kd5
Kd7 41. e6+ Ke7 42. Ke5 a6 43. a3 Ke8 44. Kd6 1-0

