{In the final two examples in this section, the characteristic of Morphy's
style that we have already identified, his tendency to complicate and/or keep
the tension, stands out even more clearly. --- White is a piece down for a
pawn. The main defect of Black's game is that his king is still not secure. At
present this is not obvious, as the white pieces are not active enough.
However, Morphy highlights this factor with his next two moves. ---} 19. f4 $1
{First of all White needs to open lines.} ({He could win a second pawn with} 
19. Qxh7 {, but} c6 {leaves Black's position very solid and White's
compensation would be insufficient; for instance, after} 20. f4 e4 21. f5 Bf6
22. Qh6 Be5 {.}) 19... e4 ({Exchanging a piece before closing the centre with} 
19... Bc5 20. Bxc5 Qxc5+ 21. Kh1 e4 {fails to improve the situation, as White
can play} 22. Bxd5 Bxd5 23. Qh5+ {and 24 Rxd5.}) 20. Rxd5 $1 ({Riskier and
more ambitious than} 20. Bxd5 Bxd5 21. Qh5+ Nf7 22. Rxd5 {, as after} Qa6 ({
the engines are not afraid to distance the queen from the action with} 22...
Qxa2 {; this continuation is "inhuman", and while it might be objectively
correct, Black seems to have a simpler defence}) 23. f5 ({if} 23. Qxh7 {then}
Qg6) 23... Qf6 24. Qxh7 Rh8 25. Qg6 Qxg6 26. fxg6 Nd6 {, Black seems to be
okay.}) 20... Bxd5 21. Qh5+ Kf8 {The choice between this move, which loses the
right to castle, and the self-pinning 21...Rg6 is a difficult one. Objectively,
they seem to be of similar strength, but from the practical viewpoint the rook
move is more complex and thus less advisable.} ({A possible continuation might
be} 21... Rg6 22. Bxd5 Bc5 23. Kh1 {and Black is faced with another difficult
decision.} Bxe3 $1 {, sacrificing his queen, is better, and after} ({After the
natural} 23... Qa6 {, White has} 24. Re1 Bxe3 25. f5 $1 {and his initiative is
very dangerous; for instance,} Nf7 26. fxg6 Qxg6 ({or} 26... hxg6 27. Qh4 $1
Kf8 28. h3 Bc5 29. Qf4) 27. Qxg6 hxg6 28. Rxe3 O-O-O 29. Be6+ Kb8 30. Kg1 {
, and in all cases White comes out the winner.}) 24. Bf7+ Nxf7 25. Qxa5 O-O-O
26. Qf5+ Rd7 27. Qxe4 Bd2 {, chances are approximately equal.}) 22. Bxd5 Rg7
23. b4 {White must dislodge the black queen so that he can advance his f-pawn.}
Qa6 24. f5 Nf7 $2 {Once again the opponent cracks under the pressure. The
knight move looks like a good idea, reinforcing the defences, but it fails
tactically.} ({It was essential to play} 24... Qf6 $1 25. Bd4 Qg5 {, when} 26.
Bxg7+ Kxg7 27. Qe8 Bf6 28. Kh1 {leads to a complex position.}) 25. f6 $1 Bxf6
26. b5 $1 Qd6 27. Bxf7 {The refutation, threatening 28 Bc5.} b6 28. Bh6 {
White has a material advantage and more active pieces, so the game is won.} Ke7
29. Bxg7 Bxg7 30. Bb3 Rf8 31. Rf7+ Rxf7 32. Qxf7+ Kd8 33. Qxg7 Qd1+ 34. Kf2
Qd2+ 35. Kg3 e3 36. Qf6+ Kc8 37. Be6+ Kb7 38. Qf3+ 1-0

[Event "odds game, New Orleans"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "1863.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Morphy, P."]
[Black "Maurian, C."]
[Result "1-0"]
[Annotator "Zenón Franco"]
[SetUp "1"]
[FEN "r5k1/2RR3N/2p1rp2/5p2/1pb5/6P1/P6P/6K1 w - - 0 34"]
[PlyCount "5"]
