[SourceDate "2016.09.01"]

{In this game Morphy played without his queen's knight but, as we can see, he
managed to regain the material and now his three remaining pieces are
attacking the black king. How to keep up the pressure? ---} 34. a4 $3 {With
this surprising move, which presents Black with two passed pawns, White
prevents the deadly rook invasion on a1 and puts Black under pressure again.} (
{There are possible mating patterns here; for instance, after} 34. Rg7+ Kh8 {
, White could play} 35. Nf8 {, threatening 36 Ng6 mate, and the knight is
taboo in view of mate in two with the rooks; but Black has} Re1+ 36. Kf2 Re2+
37. Kg1 (37. Kf3 $4 {allows the entry of the other rook with lethal effect:}
Ra3+ 38. Kf4 Rf2#) 37... Re1+ {and draws, since the attempt to flee with} 38.
Kg2 $4 {loses to} Rxa2+ 39. Kh3 Bf1+ 40. Kh4 Rxh2# {.}) 34... bxa3 $2 {We
already know why this loses.} ({Black can seek another invasion route with} 
34... Rae8 {, which is good enough to draw if he manages to find the right
moves:} 35. Rg7+ Kh8 36. Nf8 $1 {(threatening 37 Ng6 mate, or 37 Rh7+ Kg8 38
Rcg7 mate if the knight is taken; but Black has a narrow path to survival by
harassing the white king)} Re1+ 37. Kg2 Bf1+ $1 38. Kf3 ({not} 38. Kf2 $4 R8e2+
39. Kf3 Bg2+ 40. Kf4 Rf1#) 38... Be2+ $1 39. Kf2 $1 Bh5 $1 {(threatening 40...R8e2 mate)} 40. Rh7+ Kg8 41. Rxh5 R1e2+ {, and now} 42. Kf3 R8e3+ (42... R2e3+
$2 {leads to an inferior rook ending after} 43. Kf4 Re2 44. Kxf5 R2e5+ 45. Kg6
Rxh5 46. Kxh5 Rxf8 47. Rxc6 Rb8 48. Kg6 b3 49. Rc1) 43. Kf4 Re5 {(threatening
44...Rf2 mate)} 44. Rh8+ Kxh8 45. Ng6+ Kg8 46. Nxe5 fxe5+ 47. Kxf5 Rxh2 48.
Rxc6 Ra2 {should be a draw.}) ({However, the simplest way to defend was to let
the bishop cover the g6-square from d3 by playing} 34... f4 $1 {;} 35. Rd4 {
(one more example)} ({e.g. after} 35. Rg7+ Kh8 36. Nf8 Re1+ 37. Kf2 Rf1+ 38.
Kg2 f3+ 39. Kh3 Bd3 {.}) ({If instead} 35. gxf4 {, then} b3 (35... Rae8 $2 {
fails to} 36. f5 $1) 36. Rb7 b2 $1 ({not} 36... Kh8 $2 {due to} 37. Nf8 $1 {
again}) 37. Rxb2 Kh8 {and Black is okay; e.g.} 38. Rb4 Rg8+ 39. Kf2 Bd5 {
(intending ...Rge8)} 40. Rbb7 Rg2+ 41. Kf1 Ree2 42. Rd8+ Bg8 43. Nxf6 Rgf2+ 44.
Kg1 Rg2+ {with perpetual check.}) 35... b3 $1 (35... Bd5 $1 {is also fine}) 36.
Rxc4 b2 37. Nxf6+ Kf8 $1 ({better than} 37... Rxf6 $6 38. Rb7) 38. Rb4 Re1+ 39.
Kf2 b1=Q 40. Rxb1 Rxb1 41. Rd7 $1 {, followed by Nh7+, Nf6+ etc with another
draw.}) 35. Rg7+ Kh8 36. Nf8 $1 1-0

