{This game began with Morphy giving odds of a knight. His position now looks
desperate, since Black threatens mate in two with 45...Be1+. Morphy finds the
only way to save the game. ---} 45. g3+ $1 {This is the correct move order,
improving the 45 Rxe4 variation below.} ({Note that} 45. Rxe4+ $2 Kxe4 46. Kg5
{fails to draw, since Black manages to hang on to a vital pawn after} Be7+ 47.
Kxg6 h4 48. Kh5 Kf4 {and will win by capturing the pawns on g2 and h3 and
queening his h-pawn. The point is that, even though Black has the 'wrong
bishop' in respect of the h1-square, the white king will be unable to reach g1.
}) ({Black also wins after} 45. Rf6+ $2 Bf5 46. g3+ Ke5 47. Rf7 Ke6 {,
followed by 48...Be7+.}) 45... Kf5 46. Rxe4 $1 Kxe4 47. Kg5 {This is the
difference; Black is unable to save his pawn by ...h5-h4, so the exchange of
all the remaining pawns is inevitable.} Kf3 48. Kxg6 Kxg3 49. Kxh5 Kxh3 1/2-1/2

