1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. b4 Bxb4 5. c3 Ba5 {Ernest Morphy, Paul's
uncle, retreats his bishop to a5 instead of c5, as played by Paul's father in
the previous game.} 6. d4 exd4 {Fabiano Caruana has no faith in this move,
because: "The old games, such as those by Anderssen, had Black capturing on d4
and coming under attack, often losing in under 30 moves (the "Evergreen Game"
being the most famous example)."} ({The most popular treatment in the 21st
century is} 6... d6 7. Qb3 Qd7 8. dxe5 Bb6 9. a4 {has been tried in an attempt
to revive the line, but after} ({and if} 9. Nbd2 dxe5 {, Black gains a good
position and has scored well.} (9... --)) 9... Na5 10. Qa2 Nxc4 11. Qxc4 Ne7
12. Ba3 {("?" - Caruana) was tried in L.Nisipeanu-F.Caruana, Dortmund 2015,
when} (12. exd6 cxd6 13. O-O O-O {, as in H.Nakamura-V.Anand, London 2014,
"Black already has a comfortable game and is the only player with chances of
an advantage", according to Caruana.} (13... --)) 12... O-O {was good;} ({but} 
12... d5 13. exd5 Qxd5 {is even better and "White will most likely end up in a
sad endgame with a wrecked structure, and Black has a bishop pair", according
to Caruana, describing the outcome of an Evans Gambit completely lacking in
any trace of Romanticism.})) 7. O-O Bxc3 $6 {Black is now no less than three
pawns up which, other things being equal, would constitute a decisive
advantage. That's not the case here, and neglecting development is really not
advisable against the Evans Gambit. This is not exactly a losing move, but it
requires very precise defence.} ({The most popular move here is} 7... Nge7 {;})
({ahead of} 7... d6 {(as in Game 13).}) ({The third placed choice} 7... dxc3 {
is again more risky, as we shall see in Game 15.}) 8. Nxc3 dxc3 9. Ba3 ({
The alternative was another typical Evans Gambit move,} 9. Qb3 {. It is
difficult to say which is better.}) ({Löwenthal pointed out that Morphy
deviated here from the line recommended in the German magazine 'Schachzeitung'
in 1851:} 9. Ng5 {, which leads one to believe that this game was perhaps
played after 1850. In any case the position after} Nh6 {does not appear to be
better for White than Morphy's choice.}) 9... d6 {EXERCISE (easy): How did
Morphy continue? --- ANSWER:} 10. Qb3 {Of course; this is the other typical
move. There was not really any other way to activate the queen, which now
increases the pressure on f7.} Nh6 {EXERCISE: Black's response was forced. Now
what for White? --- ANSWER:} 11. Qxc3 {We need prose as well as poetry! This
regains one of the pawns and attacks g7, with an advantage in development.} Qf6
({EXERCISE: Why did Black reject} 11... O-O {- ? --- ANSWER: Because with 11
Qxc3 White also opened the long dark diagonal. He would continue} 12. Bb2 {
forcing} Qf6 {, and in the ending arising after} 13. Qxf6 gxf6 14. Bxf6 {
, the position opens up to the benefit of the bishop pair; furthermore the
white rooks stand ready to be activated on the b- and c- files. All this would
give White good compensation for the pawn.}) {EXERCISE: How did Morphy reply
to 11...Qf6 - ? --- ANSWER: With another pawn sacrifice, avoiding the exchange
of queens and reopening the a3-f8 diagonal, after which the black king will be
exposed once more.} 12. e5 $1 dxe5 ({It is noteworthy that simplifying with} 
12... Nxe5 13. Nxe5 O-O $1 {is better in this variation, when} (13... dxe5 $6
14. Rae1 {would favour the better developed side, since he would have more
open lines, as we shall see, compared with the game.} (14. --)) ({naturally not
} 13... Qxe5 $2 14. Rfe1) 14. Rac1 Qxe5 15. Qxe5 dxe5 16. Bxf8 Kxf8 {leaves
Black with three pawns for the exchange. However, this would be offset by him
having a knight on the rim and an undeveloped queenside, while the three white
pieces would be active and ready to invade after, for instance,} 17. Rfd1 {
. Admittedly, the position would not be totally clear.}) 13. Rfe1 Bd7 {
EXERCISE: The black monarch cannot castle on the kingside, so seeks refuge on
the other wing. What did Morphy play here? --- ANSWER:} 14. Rab1 $1 ({Not} 14.
Nxe5 $2 {, as this would be answered by} O-O-O {, when Black's king is safer
and he remains two pawns up, albeit still in a uncomfortable position. Morphy
opted for making the queenside the new battlefront.}) 14... O-O-O {EXERCISE:
Black's response came as no surprise. What had Morphy planned? --- ANSWER:} 15.
Ba6 $1 {An accurate shot that has the devastating effect of a knockout blow,
even though objectively it is not winning.} Na5 $2 {This loses fairly easily;
it is Black's only clearly bad move in the whole game.} ({The critical line was
} 15... bxa6 $1 16. Qb3 {, threatening mate. Although Black's position is
tottering, the game is still not at all clear.} Bg4 $1 {is better, so that the
knight on c6 remains defended by the queen. After} ({Now} 16... Be6 $2 {
fails to} 17. Qb7+ Kd7 18. Rbd1+ Nd4 {(the king cannot retreat because the
c6-knight falls)} 19. Nxe5+ Ke8 20. Rxd4 Rxd4 21. Qa8+ {(a preparatory check
to ensure that d8 is occupied)} (21. Qc6+ Kd8 22. Qa8+ Bc8 23. Nc6+ {wins more
slowly}) 21... Qd8 22. Qc6+ Rd7 23. Nxf7 $1 {and the black position collapses.}
) 17. Qb7+ Kd7 18. Rbd1+ Ke8 19. Rxd8+ Kxd8 $1 {, the white attack is
dangerous, but it is not easy find a decisive continuation.} ({Not} 19... Nxd8
$2 20. Qxc7 Bxf3 21. Rxe5+ Ne6 22. Qc8+ Qd8 23. Rxe6+ {and mates.})) {EXERCISE:
How did Morphy punish his uncle's mistake? --- ANSWER:} 16. Rec1 {Bringing up
fresh troops. Now there is no good way to defend c7.} Bc6 17. Qxa5 bxa6 18.
Qxa6+ Kd7 {White has succeeded in opening up the defences of the black king
and all the white pieces are attacking. --- EXERCISE: Now there are many good
moves; Morphy chose the strongest - what is it? --- ANSWER:} 19. Rxc6 $1 {
Of course.} Qf5 {Leaving the rook on c6 leads to mate, but there was no
defence. The rest is a massacre.} ({If} 19... Qxc6 {then} 20. Nxe5+ {wins.})
20. Rxc7+ $1 Ke8 21. Qc6+ Qd7 22. Rb8 Qxc6 23. Re7+ Kf8 24. Rxd8+ Qe8 25.
Rexe8# 1-0

