1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Bc4 Nxe4 4. Nc3 Nf6 5. Nxe5 d5 6. Bb3 Be7 (6... Bd6 7.
d4 c6 {was possible, but the text move is fine. Black can be satisfied that he
has shut the bishop out of play on b3.}) 7. d4 c6 8. O-O Nbd7 9. f4 Nb6 {
If Black wants to develop his queen's bishop along the c8-h3 diagonal he needs
to move the knight at some point, but it is better to postpone that decision.}
(9... O-O {looks better.}) 10. Qf3 h5 $2 ({Seemingly, Black was reluctant to
play} 10... O-O {on account of} 11. g4 {. That looks scary but is not
particularly dangerous, as the knight can go to e8 after, for example,} Nc4 12.
g5 {.}) {EXERCISE: How did Morphy respond? --- ANSWER:} 11. f5 {Shutting the
c8-bishop's diagonal, while opening that of his own c1-bishop.} Qc7 $6 {
Black doesn't want to castle short now, since it would be in worse
circumstances than before, but this move helps White develop.} 12. Bf4 Bd6 13.
Rae1 Kf8 $6 ({It was better to play} 13... O-O {anyway and "hope for the best".
}) {EXERCISE: How did Morphy proceed? --- ANSWER:} 14. Qg3 $1 {With the threat of
15 Ng6+.} h4 ({EXERCISE: What was White's strongest continuation after} 14...
Kg8 {- ? --- ANSWER: There are several good moves, but the line that best exploits
the awkward situation of the opposing pieces is} 15. Ng4 $1 hxg4 16. Bxd6 Qd7
17. Be7 {and Black's position is on its last legs.}) 15. Ng6+ Kg8 16. Bxd6 hxg3
17. Bxc7 fxg6 18. fxg6 gxh2+ {Black maintains material equality but the
difference in activity between the two sides is huge.} 19. Kh1 Bg4 20. Re7 Nbd7
21. Be5 Kf8 $2 {This is a fatal waste of time;} ({instead, in view of the
threat of 22 Nxd5! and wins,} 21... Rh5 $1 {was essential, to give the king
the h8-square.}) 22. Rf7+ Kg8 {EXERCISE: How did Morphy conclude the struggle
in his favour? --- ANSWER:} 23. Nxd5 $1 {The bishop exiled to b3 takes its revenge.
This is not the only move to win; he could also take on f6 first.} cxd5 24.
Bxd5 Nb6 (24... Nxd5 {allows mate in one;}) ({while} 24... Nxe5 25. R7xf6+ {
only delays the end.}) 25. Bb3 {. There is no good defence against 26 R7xf6+.}
1-0

[Event "8. First American Congress, New York"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "1857.??.??"]
[Round "4.1"]
[White "Morphy, P."]
[Black "Paulsen, L."]
[Result "1-0"]
[ECO "B40"]
[Annotator "Zenón Franco"]
[PlyCount "79"]
[EventDate "1857.??.??"]
[SourceTitle "Morphy Move By Move"]
[Source "Everyman Chess"]
[SourceDate "2016.09.01"]

{Morphy's opponent in the final was the German master Louis Paulsen, who was
living in the USA and who was a very famous player of the time. Today a
popular line of the Sicilian Defence bears his name. --- Let's look at the
first game. ---} 1. e4 c5 ({The Tarrasch French position mentioned below
arises from} 1... e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 c5 4. Ngf3 Nc6 5. exd5 exd5 6. Bb5 Bd6 7.
dxc5 Bxc5 8. O-O Nge7 {, a line in which the recently departed but never to be
forgotten Viktor Korchnoi was almost invincible as Black.}) 2. d4 cxd4 3. Nf3
e6 4. Nxd4 Bc5 {Paulsen is planning to develop his king's knight on e7.} ({
This line has been practically abandoned, displaced by} 4... a6) (4... Nc6) ({
and} 4... Nf6 {.}) 5. Nb3 ({In the fifth game of the match Morphy switched to
the stronger move} 5. Be3 {(see Game 9).}) 5... Bb6 6. Nc3 Ne7 7. Bf4 O-O $6 ({
Despite the strange appearance of Black's set-up, he could have obtained a
reasonable position after} 7... d5 8. exd5 exd5 {, when the structure
resembles that of a Tarrasch French (see 1...e6 above).}) {EXERCISE (easy):
Demonstrate that Black's last move is at least dubious. --- ANSWER:} 8. Bd6 $1
{Of course - the bishop is a very unpleasant intruder, hindering the natural
development of the black pieces.} f5 9. e5 a6 {This is a bad sign, another
loss of tempo. Black wants to prevent White from playing Nb5 at some point,
perhaps with the idea of replacing the bishop on d6.} ({Here one of the
suggestions of the analysis engines is} 9... Ng6 {. --- EXERCISE: How would
you respond in that case? --- ANSWER: There are several interesting moves,
such as} 10. g3 ({or} 10. Qd2 {, preparing the defence of the e5-pawn with 11
f4.}) ({On the other hand, it would not be the most practical (and possibly
not objectively best either) to accept the exchange sacrifice straight away
with} 10. Bxf8 Qxf8 {, since there is no way to defend the e5-pawn and Black
would have good compensation with a pawn for the exchange, the possibility of
building a strong centre, and the strength of his dark-squared bishop.})) 10.
Be2 {Morphy is looking to castle quickly on the kingside and then see how to
exploit the advantage provided by his strong bishop. This is the most sensible
and simple plan, but it's not the most energetic.} ({There are more ambitious
options, such as} 10. Qd2 {with the plan of castling queenside;}) ({or} 10. f4
{, bolstering the e5-pawn and preventing the game continuation.}) 10... Nbc6
11. O-O Rf7 {Unpinning the rook, so as to be able play ...Ng6.} 12. Kh1 ({
Another idea was} 12. Bh5 {and if} Ng6 ({while} 12... g6 13. Bf3 {, followed
by Qd2, would fail to offer Black much relief either}) {, then} 13. Qe2 {
, supporting the vital e5-pawn, and the pin is very uncomfortable for Black.})
({Now} 12. Kh1 Ng6 {can be answered by} 13. f4 {and Black can't free his
position, so Paulsen seeks another way to gain some activity.}) 12... f4 {
QUESTION: This move creates weaknesses, while the bishop on c8 is still
dormant. It looks like an emergency solution, almost smacking of desperation.
Is that so? --- ANSWER: There is a saying that we can all be brave when there
is no alternative. This move concedes the e4-square and weakens the b1-h7
diagonal. On the other hand, if White is allowed to play f2-f4, there will be
no way for Black to complicate the play. So for good or ill, f2-f4 must be
prevented. Now ...Nf5 becomes possible, in addition to ... Ng6.} 13. Ne4 Nf5 (
13... Ng6 {is answered by} 14. Bh5 {, when the exchange sacrifice would be
under rather worse conditions than before, as after} Ncxe5 15. Bxe5 Nxe5 16.
Bxf7+ Nxf7 {, White can restrain the black centre with} 17. c4 $1 {.}) 14. Bh5
{This seeks to weaken the black kingside, and succeeds, but without achieving
much.} ({Instead,} 14. Nbd2 {was interesting, and if} Nxd6 15. Nxd6 Nxe5 ({
after} 15... Rf8 16. Nf3 {, the black forces remain bottled up}) 16. Nf3 $1
Nxf3 17. Nxf7 Kxf7 18. Bxf3 d5 {, then once again} 19. c4 $1 {, and White's
greater activity is obvious.}) 14... g6 15. Bg4 Ng7 $2 {Unnecessarily passive.}
({Löwenthal's recommendation} 15... Nxd6 16. exd6 ({after} 16. Nxd6 Rf8 {
, nothing special is apparent}) 16... Ba7 {was preferable, followed by 17...b5,
or 17...b6 if necessary, releasing the c8-bishop to b7, followed by ...Rc8.
The snag is that the other bishop might become temporarily passive, but
Black's problems would be much diminished compared to the game, because there
would be no target or serious weakness in his position.}) 16. Qf3 {QUESTION:
What is the idea behind Morphy's move? Is it the best?} ({ANSWER: It is
difficult to say what the best move was here. There were other ideas, such as
simply} 16. Qe2 {. Morphy, as was his custom, was seeking to bring his pieces
into play quickly and he chose a flexible move that not only (as with 16 Qe2)
releases the inactive a1-rook, but also envisages defending his centre with
Qc3, if required.}) 16... h5 $6 {Given Black's lagging development, this move
is simply too optimistic. Here such an attack with pawns does not inspire
confidence.} ({It looks more appropriate to play} 16... Bc7 17. Qc3 Ne8 {.})
17. Bh3 Qh4 ({White could have answered} 17... g5 {with} 18. g4 $1 {, and if
Black wants to prevent the opening of the g-file, he would have had to seal up
the kingside with} h4 {, which leaves him paralysed and allows White a free
hand in the centre and on the queenside after, say,} 19. Bg2 {.}) {EXERCISE:
Black's set-up has a defect, which White can exploit with a precise series of
moves. How should he begin? --- ANSWER:} 18. Nf6+ {The first step - the knight
settles on an ideal post;} ({since} 18. Nf6+ Rxf6 19. exf6 Qxf6 20. Qxf4 {
isn't playable for Black.}) 18... Kh8 {EXERCISE: What is Morphy's next step?
--- ANSWER:} 19. Qe4 $1 {Making Black rue his decision to play 16...h5?!,
which weakened the g6-pawn.} Qg5 ({If} 19... Nf5 {then} 20. Bxf5 gxf5 21. Qf3 {
.}) 20. g3 {This is another important move, seeking to open up the game.} f3 {
This move, which tries to keep the game closed, will be quickly punished.
Naturally, opening the game is not attractive for Black, because White's lead
in development is overwhelming.} ({Nevertheless, the engines suggest} 20...
fxg3 21. fxg3 Nf5 {as a more tenacious defence, even if White is still clearly
better after} 22. Bxf5 gxf5 ({not} 22... exf5 $2 23. Qd5) 23. Qe2 {.}) {
EXERCISE: What had Morphy thought up here? --- ANSWER:} 21. Nd2 $1 {The most
elegant method of bringing another piece into the kingside campaign.} Bd8 ({
There is no good way to defend the f3-pawn, as} 21... Qxd2 22. Qxg6 {loses
straight away.}) 22. Nxf3 Qh6 23. Rg1 {QUESTION: What a strange move! ---
ANSWER: White's position is very advantageous; while 23 Rg1 is not necessarily
the best move, it has a definite idea behind it and does not worsen White's
position at all, despite its unusual appearance. Note that if Black elects to
regain the pawn with ...Bxf6 etc, it will be at the cost of remaining with
very weak dark squares. Meanwhile White needs to bring more forces into play.}
(23. Rg1 {also sets up the possibility of a timely g3-g4, opening the g-file;
e.g.} b6 24. g4 $1 hxg4 25. Ng5 $1 Qxg5 26. Rxg4 {and wins.}) 23... Bxf6 24.
exf6 Ne8 {This loses;} ({but capturing immediately with} 24... Rxf6 {would
offer no hope of salvation after} 25. Bf4 Qh7 ({or} 25... d5 26. Qe2 Qh7 27.
Ne5) 26. Rad1 ({or just} 26. c4) 26... d5 27. Qd3 {, intending 28 c4.}) 25. Bf4
Nxf6 ({Neither} 25... Qh7 26. Ng5) ({nor} 25... Qf8 26. Qxg6 {was any better.})
26. Qxc6 {Winning a piece and the game.} Qxf4 ({If} 26... bxc6 27. Bxh6 Ne4 ({
or} 27... Ng8 28. Bf4) {, then} 28. Ne5 Nxf2+ 29. Kg2 Rf6 30. Rgf1 {win}) 27.
Qxc8+ Rxc8 28. gxf4 Rxc2 29. Rac1 {Activity always!} ({Instead of, say,} 29.
Ne5 {, followed by Nd3 defending everything (which of course wins), Morphy
seeks to activate his pieces and bring the game to a rapid conclusion.}) 29...
Rxf2 30. Rc8+ Ng8 31. Ne5 {Resignation by Black would be far from premature.}
Rg7 32. Nxg6+ Kh7 33. Nf8+ Kh6 34. Nxd7 Rxd7 35. Rcxg8 Rxf4 36. Bxe6 Re7 {
It's now mate in four moves.} 37. R8g6+ Kh7 38. Bg8+ Kh8 39. Rh6+ Rh7 40. Rxh7#
1-0

