1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. b4 Bxb4 5. c3 Bc5 6. O-O d6 7. d4 exd4 8.
cxd4 Bb6 9. Nc3 Na5 10. Ng5 $6 {This is the only time on record that Morphy
faced 9...Na5; it was a blindfold game against an amateur and he decided go on
the attack, allowing the exchange of his powerful light-squared bishop in
order to gain the initiative.} ({Chigorin and Fischer both played} 10. Bg5 {
here, which is still considered the strongest move; this also permits the
c4-bishop to be exchanged following} f6 {, but at the cost of weakening Black
on the light squares.}) 10... Nxc4 11. Qa4+ c6 12. Qxc4 Nh6 13. Kh1 {It's not
a good sign that White feels he has to spend a tempo on this preparatory move;}
({but after the aggressive} 13. f4 O-O 14. f5) ({or the quieter} 13. h3 O-O 14.
Be3 {, White's attack is stopped short, for the same reason that could have
occurred in the game.}) 13... O-O 14. f4 Kh8 15. f5 {EXERCISE: Morphy is not
hiding his intention to take the black position by storm - the advance f5-f6
is in the air. How should Black respond?} f6 $2 {This prevents 16 f6, but is
not the most effective response.} ({ANSWER: Black could counter White's
expansion with} 15... d5 $1 {, since after} 16. exd5 Bxf5 {, all the black
pieces are developed and can easily contain White's attacking ambitions; e.g.}
17. dxc6 bxc6 18. Nxf7+ Nxf7 19. Rxf5 Qxd4 {. The same central counter-strike
would also be effective at the end of the lines mentioned at move 11.}) 16. Ne6
Bxe6 17. fxe6 Qe7 $2 {Another weak move, after which the situation seriously
deteriorates. --- EXERCISE (easy): What did Morphy play here? --- ANSWER:} 18.
Bxh6 {Of course; showing that 17...Ng8 would have been correct.} gxh6 {
EXERCISE: White just needs to bring his queen's rook into the game. What did
Morphy play next? --- ANSWER:} 19. Rf3 {To deploy the a1-rook to its most
effective square, f1.} Rg8 20. Raf1 Rg6 {EXERCISE: White's position now "plays
itself". How did Morphy proceed? --- ANSWER:} 21. Ne2 {The knight joins in the
offensive.} Rf8 22. Nf4 Rg5 23. d5 c5 24. Qc3 Bd8 25. Ne2 $1 {Heading for f5.}
Qg7 26. Ng3 Qc7 27. Rxf6 $1 {The most elegant way; with this combination White
is able to exploit his passed pawn on e6.} Bxf6 28. Rxf6 Rxf6 29. Qxf6+ Qg7 ({
Or} 29... Kg8 30. e7 Qc8 31. Qe6+ Qxe6 32. dxe6 {and the front e-pawn queens.})
30. Qd8+ Qg8 31. e7 Re5 32. Nh5 Rxe4 33. e8=Q ({It is mate in a few moves; e.g.
} 33. e8=Q Re1+ ({or} 33... Rxe8 34. Qf6+) 34. Qxe1 Qxd8 35. Qa1+ {.}) 1-0

[Event "14.2 Paris"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "1863.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Arnous de Riviere, J."]
[Black "Morphy, P."]
[Result "0-1"]
[ECO "C51"]
[Annotator "Zenón Franco"]
[PlyCount "76"]
