1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. b4 Bxb4 5. c3 Ba5 6. d4 d6 7. Qb3 ({Fischer
considered Morphy's choice to be superior to the more common continuation} 7.
O-O {, when} Bb6 {constitutes the Lasker Defence, "which put the Evans Gambit
out of commission", according to Fischer.}) 7... Qe7 $6 ({The main
continuation is} 7... Qd7 {, as we already noted in Game 2.}) {EXERCISE (easy):
How can Black's inaccuracy be exploited? --- ANSWER:} 8. d5 {Showing that 7...Qd7 would have been better, leaving e7 free for the knight and controlling the
a4-e8 diagonal.} Nd4 {Black's reply was forced; any other retreat and he would
lose a piece to 9 Qa4+.} 9. Bb5+ $6 {Morphy decides to enter complications.} ({
Here} 9. Qa4+ {fails to} Qd7 10. Qxa5 b6 $1 {, leading to a position in which
Black can have no complaints; e.g.} 11. Nxd4 bxa5 12. Bb5 exd4 13. Bxd7+ Kxd7
14. cxd4 {, and now he can choose between} Ba6 ({and} 14... f5 $1 {.})) ({
Taking the knight is critical:} 9. Nxd4 $1 exd4 {but now in A.Kislova-G.Gresser, Subotica 1967, White again went for the piece prematurely with} 10.
Qa4+ ({instead, simply} 10. O-O {should offer him a slight advantage}) 10...
Kd8 11. Qxa5 $2 Qxe4+ 12. Kd2 {, when} Bf5 $1 {would have been very strong; e.g.} 13. Na3 Qxg2 14. Re1 Nf6 $1 {and White's position falls apart.}) 9... c6
10. Nxd4 exd4 11. dxc6 Qxe4+ 12. Kd1 {EXERCISE: White threatens 13 Re1, while
Black must also deal with the main threat of 13 cxb7+. How to defend?} Bg4+ $2
{Not a losing move, but not the best either.} ({ANSWER: After} 12... Kf8 $1 13.
f3 Qg6 {, everything is defended and Black stands clearly better.}) 13. f3
Bxf3+ 14. gxf3 Qxf3+ 15. Kc2 Qe4+ 16. Kb2 {EXERCISE: The last few moves were
almost forced; now we are at a critical moment. What should Black play?} Bxc3+
$2 {This only helps White bring his pieces more quickly into play.} ({ANSWER:
It was essential to play} 16... bxc6 $1 {, bringing about a very unusual
position that probably offers equal chances; for example, after} 17. Rd1 ({
the alternative is} 17. Re1 Qxe1 18. Bxc6+ Ke7 19. Bxa8 Nf6 20. Qb7+ Ke6 21.
Bd2 {and "all three results are possible", as they say}) 17... Ne7 18. Rxd4
Qg2+ 19. Rd2 {.}) 17. Nxc3 dxc3+ 18. Qxc3 O-O-O 19. Re1 Qd5 20. cxb7+ Kxb7 21.
Rb1 $1 {White has several strong moves here. As we have learned to expect of
Morphy, he chooses the most elegant way to bring his inactive rook into the
game. Soon all his pieces will be working together in attack.} Nf6 22. Bc6+ ({
Both} 22. Ka1) ({and} 22. Re7+ {win more quickly (both mate in nine according
to the engines), but by now that doesn't matter.}) 22... Qxc6 23. Ka1+ Kc7 24.
Qa5+ Kc8 25. Qxa7 Nd7 26. Bd2 1-0

