1. e4 e5 2. f4 Bc5 3. Nf3 d6 4. c3 {Only on a couple of occasions did Morphy
vary from this move, which plans to occupy the centre with 5 d4.} ({One was in
a game against Thomas Barnes (London 1858) where he tried} 4. b4 $5 {;}) ({
the other was against Alphons Perrin (New York 1859), where he chose} 4. Bc4 {.
}) ({The main alternative is} 4. Nc3 {.}) 4... Bg4 (4... Bg4 {prevents} 5. d4 {
in view of} exd4 6. cxd4 Bxf3 {, when White has to play} 7. gxf3 {, which
leaves him in an awkward position after} Qh4+ 8. Ke2 Bb6 {.}) ({In one of the
earliest recorded games, Greco-NN, Europe 1620, Black tried to prevent d2-d4
with} 4... Qe7 {, but without success since Greco played} 5. d4 $1 {anyway.
After} exd4 6. cxd4 Qxe4+ $2 7. Kf2 {, the game ended quickly:} Bb4 8. a3 Ba5
9. b4 Bb6 10. Bb5+ Kf8 11. Re1 Qf5 12. Re8# {.}) ({The main reply is} 4... Nf6
{.}) 5. Be2 {Morphy wanted to maintain the central tension and try for
aggressive play with his pieces (and his pawns, as we shall see).} ({In two
casual games Capablanca preferred to stabilize the situation with} 5. fxe5 {
, as did many other twentieth-century masters, such as Réti, Euwe, Bronstein,
Larsen, planning to answer} dxe5 {with} 6. Qa4+ {(this manoeuvre is usually
credited to Marshall) to misplace Black's light-squared bishop. D.Bronstein-V.Panov, Moscow 1947, continued} Bd7 7. Qc2 Nc6 8. b4 {(evicting the bishop from
the g1-a7 diagonal, otherwise 9 b5 wins the e5-pawn)} Bd6 9. Bc4 {, followed
by d2-d3, when White's play is slightly more comfortable.}) 5... Nc6 6. b4 Bb6
7. b5 ({EXERCISE: It is a mistake to play} 7. d4 $2 {first, intending to meet
7...exd4 with the zwischenzug 8 b5, followed by 9 cxd4. Why does this fail?
--- ANSWER: Owing to} Bxf3 8. Bxf3 Nxd4 $1 {.}) 7... Na5 ({Instead, W.Steinitz-V.Green, London 1864, saw} 7... Bxf3 8. Bxf3 Nce7 9. d4 {, and here
Black committed an error with} exf4 $2 10. Bxf4 Ng6 11. Bg3 Nf6 12. Nd2 {
, when White gained a powerful centre without even having to sacrifice a pawn.
As it happens, Morphy had earlier reached the same position as White in his
1858 match with Löwenthal, who surprisingly made the same mistake (as we shall
see in Game 19).}) 8. d4 Bxf3 9. Bxf3 exd4 10. cxd4 Qf6 {EXERCISE: How did
Morphy reply to this attack on his centre pawn? --- ANSWER:} 11. Be3 {
Maintaining the mobility of his centre even at the cost of losing a tempo and
sacrificing a pawn.} ({The alternative was} 11. e5 {, but after} Qe6 12. Nc3 ({
or} 12. d5 Qe7) 12... dxe5 13. dxe5 Rd8 {, White's advanced pawns loses their
mobility and holes start to appear, without helping the development of his
pieces.}) 11... Nc4 12. Bf2 Qxf4 $6 ({Things would have been less clear after} 
12... Ba5+ $1 13. Ke2 ({not} 13. Kf1 $6 Qxf4 {, when} 14. Qa4 $2 {fails to}
Qc1+) 13... d5 $1 ({not now} 13... Qxf4 $2 14. Qa4 {and wins}) 14. exd5 Nb6 {.}
) 13. O-O {White's compensation is clear - the opening of the f-file is not
something he is sorry about and the pawn is not missed, though the sacrifice
must still be justified tactically.} Nf6 ({Here} 13... Ne3 {was to be
considered. But despite being two pawns up after} 14. Qc1 ({EXERCISE (easy):
How would} 14. Qd2 {be punished? --- ANSWER: With} Qxh2+ $1) 14... Bxd4 {
, Black is playing only with his already developed pieces, and the tactics
come out in White's favour after a series of not very obvious moves:} 15. Na3
Qh6 {(to break the pin)} 16. Rd1 $1 Be5 17. Bxe3 Qxh2+ 18. Kf1 Bxa1 {. But
instead of taking the bishop straight away, White has the zwischenzug} 19. b6
$3 {.} ({here} 19. Qxa1 Nf6 {, followed by castling, would give Black a
satisfactory position, with a rook and three pawns for the two minor pieces,
which are not very well coordinated}) 19... c6 ({If the bishop retreats with} 
19... Be5 {, say, then} 20. Nb5 {and there is no way to prevent White from
winning material; e.g.} c6 ({or} 20... Rd8 $2 21. Nxc7+ {, followed by bxa7}) 21. Nc7+ Ke7 22. Nxa8 {and Black is a piece down, as there
is no way of trapping the white knight}) ({while after} 19... axb6 20. Nb5 $1
Kf8 21. Qxa1) 20. Qxa1 Nf6 21. bxa7 {, White recaptures the bishop under far
superior conditions.}) {EXERCISE: What is White's best move?} 14. Qd3 {Morphy
contents himself with the advantage of better development and he has a clear
plan of attack in mind. First he wants to drive the black knight away, in
order to play Nc3;} ({since} 14. Nc3 $6 {immediately would be met by} Nd2 15.
Re1 O-O {.}) ({ANSWER: However, it was possible to attack at once, without
waiting for all the pieces to be developed. After} 14. Qe2 $1 Na5 {, it's
clear that the queen is much more aggressively placed on e2, since White can
now play} 15. e5 $1 {, followed by e5-e6 to open the position, when his
advantage is almost decisive; for example,} dxe5 16. dxe5 Nd7 17. e6 Nf6 18.
Bxb6 axb6 19. Bc6+ {wins the queen.}) 14... Na5 15. Nc3 O-O ({It was more
prudent to eliminate one of the white bishops with} 15... Ng4 {. After, for
example,} 16. Bxg4 Qxg4 17. Nd5 O-O 18. Ne7+ Kh8 19. Nf5 {, with the idea of
Rae1-e3, the offside black knight means that White is not worried about being
a pawn down, but neither does Black have any immediate problems.}) {EXERCISE:
All the white pieces are now in play, apart from the rook on a1. There are
several possibilities here - which do you think Morphy chose? --- ANSWER:} 16.
g3 {With this and the following move Morphy tries to exploit the uncomfortable
position of the black queen. --- QUESTION: This isn't very threatening or
impressive though, is it? --- ANSWER: Morphy plays with what he has. The
position is approximately equal for now.} Qh6 17. Kg2 {Morphy continues with
his idea; now he's controlling h3.} Rae8 18. Rae1 Kh8 $6 {This is very passive;
} (18... Qg6 $5 {would have placed more obstacles in White's way.}) 19. Be3 Qg6
{EXERCISE: How did White follow up the plan initiated with 16 g3 - ? ---
ANSWER:} 20. Ne2 {Of course;} ({the threat after} 20. Ne2 {is now} -- 21. Nf4
Qh6 22. Ne6 {. The move is a simple one but must be justified tactically,
since the e4-pawn is left hanging.}) 20... h6 {This prepares a bolthole for
the queen.} (20... Nxe4 $2 {was impossible owing to} 21. Nf4 Qf5 22. g4 {
and wins.}) ({The exchange sacrifice} 20... Rxe4 21. Nf4 Rxf4 22. Qxg6 hxg6 23.
Bxf4 Bxd4 {was also unsatisfactory. Although Black has no less than three
pawns for the exchange, his pieces are placed so awkwardly, and White's so
well, that his compensation is insufficient. Here's a sample continuation:} 24.
Re7 Bb6 25. g4 $1 Kg8 26. g5 Nh5 27. Bd2 Nc4 28. Bc1 a6 29. Bd5 Ne5 30. Bb2 {
and f7 falls with a big advantage to White.}) 21. Bd2 $1 {QUESTION: What's so
good about this? Wasn't it better to play the obvious 21 Nf4 first?} ({ANSWER:
You're right that} 21. Nf4 {was a good alternative, though after} Qh7 {, the
best move is probably} 22. Bd2 {anyway. --- Morphy's choice strikes me as
admirable - the idea is to lend more strength to the future advance e4-e5 
(which will come after the preparatory Nf4). Moving the bishop to d2 not only
activates the rook on e1, it also puts pressure on the knight on a5, while the
bishop may prove useful on the a3-f8 diagonal.}) 21... d5 $2 {A very weak
reply; Black cracks under the pressure and makes White's task easier - after a
short sequence Black loses at least a pawn. However, his position was now very
uncomfortable in any event;} ({for instance, the strength of 21 Bd2 can be
seen after} 21... c6 22. Nf4 Qh7 23. Bb4 {.}) ({The exchange sacrifice} 21...
Rxe4 22. Nf4 Rxf4 23. Qxg6 fxg6 24. Bxf4 Bxd4 {might again be considered, even
if the evaluation is not very different than on the previous move: White has
the advantage after} 25. h4 ({or even} 25. Re7 g5 26. Bd2 {, but this was
preferable for Black than the text move.})) 22. Nf4 Qh7 23. e5 Qxd3 24. Nxd3 {
The d5-pawn will fall and with it Black's whole position.} Nc4 {Black decides
to sacrifice the exchange instead.} ({After} 24... Nh7 25. Bxd5 Rd8 26. Bxf7
Rxd4 27. Bg6 {, Black's position is hopeless;}) ({and} 24... Ne4 25. Bb4 Rg8
26. Bxe4 dxe4 27. Rxe4 f6 28. e6 {is little better.}) 25. Bb4 Ne4 26. Bxf8 Rxf8
27. Nf4 $5 {Morphy prefers to play actively with his 31st move in mind.} ({
Objectively, the straightforward} 27. Bxe4 dxe4 28. Nc5 {was stronger.}) 27...
Ned2 (27... Ncd2 $2 28. Bxe4 Nxf1 29. Bxd5 {is worse for Black.}) {EXERCISE:
What had Morphy planned here? --- ANSWER:} 28. Bxd5 $1 {He wants to return the
exchange in return for capturing an important pawn, all based on concrete
tactics, as we keep seeing.} Nxf1 29. Bxc4 Nd2 30. Bd5 Bxd4 $2 ({Black had
clearly overlooked Morphy's reply, otherwise he would have played} 30... g5 $1
{, when he is still in the game.}) {EXERCISE: What was that key move that
Morphy had prepared? --- ANSWER:} 31. e6 $1 {He creates a passed pawn which
will decide the game. The pawn is immune from capture owing to Ng6+.} g5 32. e7
Re8 33. Bxf7 gxf4 34. gxf4 Rxe7 35. Rxe7 1-0

