{Morphy also won the tenth game after Löwenthal blundered in a slightly worse
position, bringing the score to 7½-2½; but in the eleventh game Morphy
chose the then relatively unexplored Sicilian Defence and landed in an
inferior position himself - after 14 moves he was down a piece for two pawns
and, despite some ingenious resistance, Löwenthal went on to win. --- Let's
now look at the twelfth game. ---} 1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 exd5 {We know
that Morphy preferred an open type of game to a closed one. This Exchange
Variation frees the 'French bishop' on c8 and leads to a fairly level position;
nevertheless, Morphy played it to win, not with the intention of making a draw.
} 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bd3 Be6 $6 {This isn't the most flexible move - at this stage
it's impossible to be sure whether this is the best square for the bishop.
Black usually develops the other bishop first, to e7 or d6;} ({while for those
seeking to complicate the games as soon as possible there is} 5... c5 {.}) 6.
O-O Bd6 7. Nc3 c6 {EXERCISE: What do you think Morphy played in this position?
--- ANSWER:} 8. Ne5 {The most ambitious move, occupying a central square with
the idea of playing f2-f4.} ({Another idea is} 8. Ng5 {, trying to punish the
early development of the bishop to e6, and if the bishop retreats then 9 Re1+.}
) 8... Qb6 {EXERCISE: What had Morphy planned against this counter-attack? ---
ANSWER:} 9. Be3 {The house speciality; Morphy has no hesitation in sacrificing
a pawn to obtain a lead in development.} ({Today's analysis engines are
initially attracted to an 'inhuman' manoeuvre which it is doubtful Morphy
would ever have chosen:} 9. Re1 O-O (9... Qxd4 $2 {is bad on account of} 10.
Nb5 $1 ({which is even better than} 10. Nxf7)) 10. Na4 Qa5 11. c3 {- can it
really be good to place the knight on a4? The engines begin to doubt the
strength of this original idea after} Nbd7 {.}) 9... Nbd7 {Rather inconsistent;
} (9... Qxb2 {was playable, and if} 10. Qe1 Qb6 (10... Bb4 11. Bd2 {is dubious
for Black}) 11. Rb1 Qc7 {, though White would have sufficient compensation
after} 12. Bg5 {, intending f2-f4.}) 10. f4 {Supporting the knight, and Black
must also take into account the advance f4-f5 at an opportune moment.} Bxe5 $1
{Now White's f-pawn will never go to f5, and his menacing initiative will lose
strength following the exchange of two minor pieces.} ({Instead,} 10... Nxe5 $2
11. fxe5 Bxe5 {fails to} 12. Na4 $1 {, winning material;}) ({while if} 10...
Qxb2 {then} 11. Qe1 Bb4 ({not now} 11... Qb6 $2 12. f5) 12. Bd2 {is strong,
with the threat of 13 Nxd7 and 14 f5;} ({and} 12. Rb1 {is attractive too.}))
11. fxe5 Ng4 12. Qd2 Nxe3 13. Qxe3 Qxb2 {QUESTION: Is this a good moment to
take the pawn? --- ANSWER: Yes. It is less risky now, thanks to the previous
exchanges; furthermore, the pawn is some consolation to Black for having less
space. --- EXERCISE: How did Morphy react to the loss of his b-pawn? ---
ANSWER:} 14. Ne2 {There was no way to exploit the position of the queen on b2
immediately, so Morphy improves the position of his threatened knight, which
will now find a good square on f4, from where it will put pressure on the
bishop on e6 and might eventually go to h5.} (14. Ne2 {also creates the
immediate threat of} -- 15. Rab1 Qa3 ({not} 15... Qxa2 $4 16. Ra1 Qb2 17. Rfb1
{, winning the queen}) 16. Rxb7 {, invading the seventh rank with a big
advantage.}) 14... Qa3 15. Nf4 Qe7 ({Black parries the threat of} 15... -- 16.
Nxe6 fxe6 17. Bg6+ {.}) ({This could also have been achieved by playing} 15...
O-O-O {, when White might have replied} 16. Rfb1 {, intending Rb3 and a2-a4,
with compensation for the pawn, if no clear advantage.}) 16. Rab1 O-O-O {
Black was probably regretting not having castled on the previous move.} ({
Leaving his king in the centre isn't at all attractive: for instance,} 16...
Nb6 $6 {would allow} 17. Nh5 $1 g6 18. Ng7+ {(seeking to utilize the f-file)} (
{as opposed to} 18. Nf6+) 18... Kd8 19. a4 $1 Nxa4 20. Rf6 Nb6 21. Nxe6+ fxe6
22. Rbf1 {with a crushing position.}) {EXERCISE: How did Morphy proceed in
this position? --- ANSWER:} 17. Be2 $1 {Clearing the third rank for the white
queen. The target (the black king) is now a fixed one, and White requires the
presence of his queen in the attack.} ({Another good idea was} 17. a4 $1 {
, followed by a4-a5, and might be even more accurate as it would prevent
Black's reply -} Nb6 18. a5 Nc4 {now loses to} 19. Bxc4 dxc4 20. d5 $1 {
and Qxa7.}) 17... Nb6 18. Qb3 Rd7 {Defending the second rank;} (18... Kb8 {
was the standard alternative.}) 19. Nd3 {We are reaching the critical moment.
Black's previous move seemed to encourage this knight manoeuvre, threatening
Nc5, but the situation remains rather unclear because it also allows the black
knight's next move.} Nc4 20. Nc5 {EXERCISE: It's not hard to see that the
black position is a difficult one in view of the weakened position of his king
and White's greater piece activity, but there is a defence. What should Black
play here?} Rc7 $2 {Löwenthal fails to offer the most tenacious resistance and
his position quickly collapses.} ({ANSWER: It was essential to play} 20... Nd2
{, which looks rather dubious but isn't easy to refute.} 21. Qg3 {(eyeing g7)
seems a better try, but after, for example,} ({If White tries to attack
directly with} 21. Qa4 {then} Kb8 $1 {is both forced and good, since} 22. Qxc6
$2 {fails to} Nxb1 23. Rxb1 Ka8 $1 {.} (23... --)) 21... Nxf1 22. Bxf1 b6 ({not
} 22... Rc7 $2 23. Nxb7 $1 Rxb7 $2 24. Ba6 {and wins}) ({nor} 22... Rg8 $2 {
for the same reason}) 23. Nxd7 Kxd7 24. Qxg7 Qf8 25. Qg3 {, Black is only
slightly worse.}) 21. Qa4 {With this attack on the a7-pawn White's advantage
becomes clear.} ({Morphy himself suggested playing} 21. Bxc4 {first, which is
also good, though no better than the text.}) 21... b6 ({After} 21... b5 22.
Qa6+ Kd8 23. Bxc4 dxc4 24. a4 {, White's initiative is decisive.}) ({From a
practical point of view it was perhaps more tenacious to play} 21... Kb8 $5 22.
Na6+ Ka8 23. Nxc7+ Qxc7 {, when Black has a pawn for the exchange with hopes
of holding on the light squares.}) 22. Bxc4 {Eliminating the most effective
defender and opening lines against the black king.} bxc5 ({If} 22... dxc4 {then
} 23. Rxb6 $1 {wins.}) 23. Ba6+ Kd7 {EXERCISE: What is White's strongest move
now? --- ANSWER:} 24. Bb7 $1 {With a threat that Black overlooks.} Rd8 {
This loses quickly, but there was no real improvement.} ({After} 24... Kd8 25.
Bxc6 cxd4 26. Qa5 Kc8 {, for instance, one way to break in is} 27. Qa6+ Kd8 28.
Rb8+ Bc8 29. Qa5 $1 Qxe5 {(otherwise 30 Qxd5+ etc)} 30. Bb7 {and there is no
defence, since} Ke7 {runs into} 31. Re1 {.}) {EXERCISE: How did Morphy force
Black to resign? --- ANSWER:} 25. Bxc6+ $1 ({If} 25. Bxc6+ Rxc6 {then} 26. Rb7+
Ke8 27. Rxe7+ Kxe7 28. Qxc6 {wins.}) 1-0

[Event "22. London (match)"]
