{In the fourth game of the match, the players repeated the opening moves of
the second game. ---} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. d3 Bc5 {
In those days, when the theory of the openings was in its infancy, Morphy was
critical of 5 d3, on the grounds that it allows the development of this bishop
to c5, leading to equality.} (5... b5 6. Bb3 Bc5 7. c3 {reaches the position
in the note to move seven below;} ({although, at the time of writing,} 7. Nc3 {
is more popular via this move order, and if} d6 {then} 8. Nd5 {.})) 6. c3 ({
In the only game where Morphy reached a position with Bb3 (via} 6. O-O b5 7.
Bb3 {), after his retirement, against J.Sicre in Havana 1862, he played} d6 8.
c3 h6 {.}) 6... b5 7. Bc2 ({More frequently the bishop retreats with} 7. Bb3 {
instead, although that position is usually reached by via 5...b5 (see above).})
7... d5 $1 {The retreat of the bishop to c2 seems to encourage this move,
although Steinitz considered it to be premature. It comes as no surprise that
Morphy should seek active piece play, as long as there no clear reason not to.}
8. exd5 ({In the 16th game of the Steinitz-Chigorin World Championship match
in Havana 1892, Steinitz played} 8. Qe2 {, although he failed to gain any
advantage after} O-O 9. Bg5 dxe4 ({and Black has a good alternative in} 9... d4
{, played successfully by Tarrasch and more recently by Ivan Sokolov}) 10. dxe4
h6 {.}) 8... Nxd5 9. h3 {Preventing the threat of ...Bg4, which would gain in
strength once White has completed his plan of advancing with d3-d4.} O-O 10.
O-O h6 {It is possible that this move, which weakens the kingside and might
have been very important in the game, could have been postponed.} ({Instead,
the prophylactic retreat} 10... Bb6 $1 {was interesting.}) 11. d4 {This was
Anderssen's idea.} ({The alternative was} 11. Nxe5 Nxe5 12. d4 {, when Morphy
may have chosen} Qf6 ({and rejected} 12... Bd6 {, which concedes a slight
initiative to White after} 13. dxe5 Bxe5 14. f4 Bf6 15. Qd3 g6 16. f5 g5 17.
Nd2) {, with good piece play for the pawn after} 13. dxc5 Bb7 {, followed by ...Rad8.}) 11... exd4 12. cxd4 Bb6 13. Nc3 Ndb4 $6 {The move isn't a bad one in
itself, but it forms part of a dubious plan. --- QUESTION: Really? It looks
like a "free move" that forces the bishop to retreat to the not very
advantageous b1-square; then in order to evict the knight from b4 White would
have to play a2-a3, another move of debatable utility. Isn't that so? ---
ANSWER: What we have here is a slightly atypical isolated queen's pawn (IQP)
position, with a black pawn on b5 (rather than b7) and a bishop on b6 (rather
than e7). The absence of the e7-bishop means that Black's kingside is slightly
weakened. Nevertheless, his position is a good one; he should be able to cope
with any problems on the kingside, while the bishop on b6, aiming at d4, can
be an advantage. --- As for the utility of a2-a3 and the inconvenience of
having to retreat the bishop to b1, the negative side dissipates when we
consider that one of the typical plans for White in IQP positions is to play
Bc2 (or Bb1) and Qd3, for which it's useful to insert a2-a3 to prevent a
subsequent ...Nb4.} ({There were several good moves instead of 13...Ndb4. The
most appropriate, with a view to a long struggle, was} 13... Nf6 $1 {, and
after} 14. Be3 {, Black can choose between} Bb7 (14... Be6) ({and} 14... Re8 {.
})) 14. Bb1 $6 {White offers the d4-pawn;} ({defending it with} 14. Be3 $2 {
would entail simply leaving the isolani as a weakness after} Nxc2 {.}) ({
However,} 14. Be4 $1 {was a good zwischenzug, and if} f5 {then} 15. Bb1 {
, when the inclusion of ...f7-f5 naturally weakens Black's position; after}
Nxd4 16. Nxd4 Qxd4 ({not} 16... Bxd4 $4 17. Qb3+) 17. Qf3 {, followed by a2-a3
and Rd1, White would have more than enough compensation for the pawn, as
Maróczy pointed out.}) 14... Be6 $2 {This move is based on a tactical error.} (
{Although it wasn't his intention, Black should have played} 14... Nxd4 {
, and even if} 15. Nxd4 {and 16 Qf3 still gives White some compensation, Black
certainly isn't worse.}) 15. a3 Nd5 {EXERCISE: This position was reached in
both games two and four of the match. Surprisingly, neither player noticed a
strong continuation for White here. Can you find it?} 16. Be3 $6 ({In game two
Anderssen played} 16. Ne2 $6 Nf6 17. Be3 {, which we shall examine in
Supplementary Game 29.1. The text move is a slight improvement, defending the
centre pawn by developing the bishop at once and maintaining the harmony of
White's position.}) ({The petite combinaison} 16. Nxb5 {is harmless: Black can
choose between} axb5 ({or} 16... Nf6 17. Nc3 Nxd4 18. Nxd4 Bxd4 {with an equal
position}) 17. Qc2 Nf6 18. Qxc6 Bd5 $1 19. Qc3 ({taking the second pawn is
risky, as after} 19. Qxb5 Bxf3 20. gxf3 Ra5 {, the d4-pawn is lost and White's
king is left very vulnerable}) 19... Re8 {, when his great piece activity
compensates for the pawn.}) ({ANSWER: But} 16. Qc2 $1 {is very strong. Black
would have to resign himself to playing a pawn down after} g6 (16... Nf6 $2 {
loses to} 17. Ne4 $1 {, based on the weakness of the loose knight on c6}) ({and
} 16... f5 {is no better, since White can exploit another tactical weakness 
(the a2-g8 diagonal) with} 17. Re1 Qf6 18. Rxe6 $1 Qxe6 19. Nxd5 Qxd5 20. Ba2)
17. Bxh6 {. --- QUESTION: Isn't it odd that neither of the two players saw
this over the board, and even odder that it wasn't found after game two? ---
ANSWER: Yes, it's very strange. But times have changed and things are very
different today, when top games can be watched 'live' in the Internet and a
blunder is flagged up by the engines the second after it is made.}) 16... Nf6 {
Anticipating the white battery after 17 Qc2 or 17 Qd3.} 17. Qd2 {Now Black has
to check whether 18 Bxh6 is really a threat or not.} Re8 {Bringing the rook
into play and giving his king an escape square that might prove useful in some
lines.} 18. Rd1 ({Black has concluded that the sacrifice on h6 can't be
prevented, but neither does it bring White any advantage; for example,} 18.
Bxh6 gxh6 19. Qxh6 Nxd4 20. Rd1 (20. Ng5 $2 {is parried by} Nf5) 20... Bb3 ({or
} 20... Bc4) 21. Ng5 ({or just} 21. Qg5+ Kf8 22. Qh6+ {etc}) 21... Qd6 22. Bh7+
Nxh7 23. Qxh7+ Kf8 24. Re1 Qf6 25. Qh4 Kg8 26. Qh7+ Kf8 {with a draw.}) 18...
Bd5 {Morphy opts for a strategy of blockade, at the cost of his light-squared
bishop.} ({Instead,} 18... Bb3 $1 {was interesting, to drive the rook off the
central file and weaken the defences of the d4-pawn. After} 19. Rc1 Qd7 {
, Black seems to be fine, since} 20. Bxh6 {can now be met by} Nxd4 $1 {
straight away, as well as taking on h6.}) 19. Ne5 {Faithful to his style,
Anderssen offers a pawn.} ({A more positional player would have considered} 19.
Nxd5 Qxd5 20. Ba2 {with a good position for White.}) {EXERCISE: What did
Morphy play here? Do you think he accepted the pawn? --- ANSWER: No.} 19... Qd6
$1 ({The greedy} 19... Nxe5 $2 {runs into} 20. dxe5 Rxe5 ({or} 20... Bxe3 21.
fxe3 Rxe5 22. e4) 21. Bxb6 cxb6 22. Ba2 {, winning a piece due to the pin on
the d-file. The attempted counter-pin after} Qe7 ({or} 22... Qe8) 23. Bxd5 ({
alternatively, White can throw in} 23. f4 $1 {, eliminating all counterplay
before capturing on d5}) 23... Rd8 {fails to} 24. Re1 $1 Nxd5 25. Rxe5 Qxe5 26.
Rd1 {and Black is pinned again.}) 20. Qc2 $2 {Anderssen insists on attacking,
but Morphy will show that this is unsound.} ({Here} 20. Bxh6 {was also
inadequate in view of} gxh6 21. Qxh6 Nxe5 22. Nxd5 ({not} 22. dxe5 $2 Bxf2+ $1
23. Kh1 ({or} 23. Kxf2 Ng4+) 23... Rxe5 {and wins}) 22... Qxd5 23. Qxf6 Rad8 $1
{. Despite the engines' interesting resource} 24. Bh7+ $1 Kxh7 25. Qh4+ Kg8 26.
dxe5 {, aiming for perpetual check, Black can play} Bd4 27. Qg5+ Kf8 28. Qh6+
Ke7 29. Qh4+ f6 $1 {, when he still has some chances.}) ({If White lines up
further forward with} 20. Qd3 {.} Nxe5 ({Black might strengthen his position
with} 20... Rad8 {, as suggested by Zukertort. White should then forget about
the attack and play something like} 21. Nxd5 ({he can't support his e5-knight
with} 21. f4 $2 {because of} Bc4 $1 22. Nxc4 bxc4 23. Qd2 Qe6 {, winning})
21... Qxd5 22. Nf3 {, followed by Ba2, with equal chances.}) 21. dxe5 Rxe5 {
looks even better for Black, as} 22. Bf4 {can be met by} Qc5 23. Qd2 Rh5 {
, keeping the extra pawn.}) ({Another possibility was} 20. Nxd5 Nxd5 {, when
one complex line, wholly in the style of Anderssen, was} 21. Qc2 Nxe3 22. Qh7+
(22. fxe3 $5 {is also possible}) 22... Kf8 23. Nxf7 $1 Kxf7 24. fxe3 Ke7 25.
Be4 {, followed by Rac1. Despite having only a pawn for the piece, White has
obvious compensation as both Black's minor pieces are out of play and his king
is weak.}) {EXERCISE: How did Morphy refute Anderssen's idea? --- ANSWER:}
20... Nxd4 $1 {After the necessary calculation, Morphy exploits the greater
centralization of his pieces.} 21. Bxd4 Bxd4 22. Nxd5 (22. Ng4 {isn't
dangerous in view of} Bb7 ({or} 22... c6 {, and with his rook on a1 White's
attack is going nowhere after} 23. Nxf6+ Qxf6 24. Qh7+ $2 Kf8 25. Qh8+ Ke7 26.
Nxd5+ cxd5 {.}) ({The analysis engines consider} 22... Nxg4 {to be even better,
seeing no danger to the black king after} 23. hxg4 Rad8 {; the queen check on
h7 is again harmless, as White is unable to back it up.})) 22... Qxe5 23. Nxf6+
Qxf6 24. Qh7+ Kf8 25. Be4 {White is finally ready to bring his last piece into
play, but at the cost of a pawn and weaknesses at b2 and f2. This is one of
the rare instances where the presence of opposite-coloured bishops fails to
help the attacker.} Rad8 $1 {Rather than take on f2 and risk trouble on the
f-file, Black prepares to win the b2-pawn safely.} ({Not yet} 25... Bxb2 $2 {
due to} 26. Rd7 $1 {and White's attack springs to life.}) 26. Kh1 ({After} 26.
Rf1) ({or} 26. Rd2 {, capturing on b2 is still fine for Black.}) 26... Bxb2 27.
Rab1 Rxd1+ 28. Rxd1 Qxf2 29. Qh8+ Ke7 30. Qh7 Be5 {Three pawns up Morphy is
content to simplify to an easily winning position.} ({Otherwise} 30... Rd8 {
was good, since} 31. Rxd8 {loses to} Qe1+ 32. Kh2 Be5+ {etc.}) 31. Bf3 Qg3 32.
Kg1 Qg6 {This is good enough to win, even if Morphy might have been expected
to seek to conclude the struggle in the middlegame;} ({for example,} 32... Bd4+
$1 33. Kh1 ({or} 33. Rxd4 Qe1+ 34. Kh2 Qe5+) 33... g6 $1 34. Qxh6 Rh8 35. Qd2
Rxh3+ $1 36. gxh3 Qxh3+ 37. Qh2 Qxf3+ 38. Qg2 Qxd1+ 39. Kh2 Be5+ {etc.}) 33.
Qxg6 fxg6 34. Bb7 Rb8 35. Bxa6 c6 36. Kf2 $6 {Anderssen doesn't defend in the
most tenacious manner.} ({It was better to play} 36. Rb1 {, intending a3-a4 to
free the bishop, even if it means Black gaining one or two passed pawns as a
result.}) 36... Bd6 37. Rd3 $6 ({Here} 37. Ra1 {was more stubborn, with the
same idea of playing a3-a4.}) 37... Kd7 38. Ke2 Ra8 $1 {Another pawn falls and
the rest is simple. All Black needs to do is advance the connected passed
pawns with the necessary modicum of care.} 39. Bb7 Rxa3 40. Rd1 Kc7 41. Bc8
Ra2+ 42. Kf3 Bc5 43. Be6 Rf2+ 44. Kg3 Rf6 45. Rd7+ Kb6 46. Bg4 Bd6+ 47. Kh4 c5
48. Bf3 c4 49. Rxg7 Rf4+ 50. Bg4 c3 51. g3 Rxg4+ 0-1

