1. -- {The only games of Morphy's that could be considered "official" are:}
(1. -- {First American Chess Congress, New York, 6 October-10 November 1857
--- Rd.1: P.Morphy 3-0 J.Thompson --- Rd.2: P.Morphy 3-0 A.B.Meek ---
Semi-final: P.Morphy 3½-½ T.Lichtenhein --- Final: P.Morphy 6-2 L.Paulsen 
(+5, =2, -1)}) (1. -- {Match, London, 19 July-22 August 1858 --- P.Morphy 10-4
J.Löwenthal (+9, =2, -3)}) (1. -- {Match, London, September 1858 --- P.Morphy
5½-2½ D.Harrwitz (+5, =1, -2)}) (1. -- {Match, Paris, 20-28 December 1858
--- P.Morphy 8-3 A.Anderssen (+7, =2, -2)}) (1. -- {Match, Paris,
February-March 1859 --- P.Morphy 7½-½ A.Mongredien}) (1. -- {Morphy played
many games at various odds - a knight; pawn and move; pawn and two moves;
pawn and three moves - and won most of them. He also played multiple games
blindfold with success. --- His most remarkable results giving odds of the
queen's knight were against two former rivals: --- New York, May 1959: Morphy
5½-3½ J.Thompson (+5, =1, -3) --- New York, July 1959: Morphy 6½-2½ T.Lichtenhein (+6, =1, -4)}) (1. -- {Other significant results: --- New Orleans,
May 1850: P.Morphy 3-0 J.Löwenthal (or 2½-½) --- New York, 28-30 November
1857 (Morphy giving pawn and move): P.Morphy 4½-½ C.H.Stanley --- London,
April 1959 (Morphy giving the queen's knight): P.Morphy 7-2 T.H.Worrall (+7,
=0, -2) --- New York, May 1859 (Morphy giving the queen's knight): P.Morphy
5½-½ F.Perrin --- London, August 1959 (Morphy giving pawn and move): P.Morphy 6-1 J.Owen (+5, =2, -0)}) *



